t-coming-soon-virtual-events/\">Coming Soon: Virtual Events for The Events Calendar</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Hazel\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10203:\"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Toward the end of March 2020, I sent my boss a Slack message: â€œYou know, we should really put some work into pulling together a product to help people with virtual events.â€Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">â€œTell me more,â€ he replied.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At the time, I wasnâ€™t sure exactly what this product would entail. But I knew there was a need for a plugin tailored for </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/virtual-event-resources/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">virtual events</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, especially as event managers around the world scrambled to adjust while a pandemic swept the globe. Now, a little over two months later, Iâ€™m excited to share the full story behind why we decided to build Virtual Events, the latest addition to The Events Calendar suite of tools.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">First, letâ€™s back up again to March. Iâ€™ve </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/event-management/on-being-an-event-planner-during-a-pandemic/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">talked about this before</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, but in my other life, Iâ€™m an event organizer, and I have been for about as long as I can remember. When COVID-19 hit, every piece of event revenueâ€”for me and for other event plannersâ€”stopped cold. No new sponsors. </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/event-management/expect-the-unexpected-how-to-cancel-an-event/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Cancelled events</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Refunded memberships. I immediately went to work trying to transition to virtual events on my own siteâ€™s calendar where I run a directory for family-friendly events, but I soon realized that it was going to be a huge pain in the ass.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Meanwhile at The Events Calendar, our team got to work creating </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/virtual-event-resources/#helpful-extensions\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">extensions</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and snippets to help our plugins run more smoothly for virtual events. Thatâ€™s when we began thinking about creating a product specifically designed for virtual events, instead of just focusing on workarounds. By April, it was clear that virtual events were around to stay, and we wanted to create a plugin that could make the most of those events.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We started digging in to see what customers needed to make virtual events work on their sites. Hereâ€™s what we learned:</span></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2088305\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1.png\" alt=\"Results of a survey from The Events Calendar that show 76.9% of respondents want our tools to integrate with video conferencing and live streaming.\" width=\"1334\" height=\"700\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1.png 1334w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-300x157.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-665x349.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-140x73.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-768x403.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-430x226.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-645x338.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-1068x560.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-460x241.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-1074x564.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-512x269.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-707x371.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-600x315.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey1-500x262.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1334px) 100vw, 1334px\" /></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2088341\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2.png\" alt=\"Responses to a survey that shows 83.2% of users want The Events Calendar to integrate with Zoom.\" width=\"1298\" height=\"966\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2.png 1298w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-300x223.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-665x495.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-114x85.png 114w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-768x572.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-430x320.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-645x480.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-1068x795.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-460x342.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-1074x799.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-512x381.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-707x526.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-600x447.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/survey2-500x372.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1298px) 100vw, 1298px\" /></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Number one on the list: Zoom integration.Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I think youâ€™ll like this feature as much as I do.Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hereâ€™s what I was doing on my own calendar </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">before</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Virtual Events: Go to Zoom, create a link, go to my email service, set up a trigger to email the Zoom link when guests RSVP (because I donâ€™t want to share the Zoom link publicly), then on the day of the event, add the Zoom link to the event page, in case anyone missed it.Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There had to be a better way, right?</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I know I sound like a lady in an infomercial. But our product developers at The Events Calendar agreed: There definitely needed to be a better way, and they were able to make it happen. Our Virtual Events plugin integrates with Zoom to streamline all of these steps, and even allows you to generate Zoom meeting links right from your WordPress dashboard.</span></p>\n<div id=\"attachment_2089834\" style=\"width: 772px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2089834\" class=\"wp-image-2089834 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail.jpg\" alt=\"First look at the Zoom integration in Virtual Events\" width=\"762\" height=\"776\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail.jpg 762w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-295x300.jpg 295w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-665x677.jpg 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-83x85.jpg 83w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-430x438.jpg 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-645x657.jpg 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-460x468.jpg 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-512x521.jpg 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-520x530.jpg 520w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-300x306.jpg 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-600x611.jpg 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/06/VE_zoom-detail-500x509.jpg 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 762px) 100vw, 762px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2089834\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">First look at the Zoom integration in Virtual Events</p></div>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">So many customers weâ€™ve heard from are spending too much time trying to find workarounds to hide Zoom links, embed videos, and send reminder emails. Iâ€™m happy to say Virtual Events for WordPress does all of this and more.Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For now (although it changes every day), nearly everyone I know in the events business assumes that large-scale events arenâ€™t coming back until late 2021. Regardless, weâ€™re all trying to become pros at virtual events as quickly as possible. Iâ€™m inspired by examples of business owners quickly adapting, like Meg Chaloner of </span><a href=\"https://sipandscript.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Sip and Script</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, who figured out a way to transition her nationwide calligraphy workshops into fun and interactive virtual events.Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Plain and simple, we built Virtual Events to make your life as an event organizer easier. While some of our customers have made The Events Calendar and Event Tickets work for virtual events, the reality is those plugins were built with live events in mindâ€”not webinars, online classes, and virtual conferences. Virtual events require their own calendar solutions, and thatâ€™s why weâ€™ve spent the past few months hard at work on this plugin.Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Stay tuned in the coming weeks as we announce the official launch of Virtual Events (including a super low introductory price so you can get started ASAP without breaking the bank). In the meantime, check out our </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/virtual-event-resources/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">virtual event resources page</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to master the ins and outs of planning online events.</span></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/new-product-coming-soon-virtual-events/\">Coming Soon: Virtual Events for The Events Calendar</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:58:\"How to Turn Anything Into an Event Your Audience Will Love\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:94:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-turn-anything-into-an-event-your-audience-will-love/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 03 Jun 2020 14:48:58 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Blog\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"Event Management\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Tips & Tricks\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Virtual Events\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2047938\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:632:\"<p>The mere thought of planning an event can be daunting: All that time and effort, all the logistics to coordinate, and all the costs that can add up quickly, plus a whole different set of concerns for virtual events, like choosing the best livestreaming platform or figuring out online ticketing. But creating a new event&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-turn-anything-into-an-event-your-audience-will-love/\">How to Turn Anything Into an Event Your Audience Will Love</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Lauren\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7163:\"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The mere thought of</span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/the-only-event-management-checklist-youll-ever-need/\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">planning an event</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> can be daunting: All that time and effort, all the logistics to coordinate, and all the costs that can add up quickly, plus a whole different set of concerns for </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/virtual-event-resources/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">virtual events</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, like choosing the best livestreaming platform or figuring out online ticketing.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But creating a new event doesnâ€™t have to be an epic undertaking. In fact, youâ€™re probably already doing things that you can easily turn into events your customers will love. All it takes is a little creativity.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Why bother making an ordinary occasion into a bonafide event? For starters, events help boost sales. Theyâ€™re also a powerful marketing tool that help you stand out from competition and increase customer loyalty.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read on for a few ideas for how to take what youâ€™re already doing and turn it into events that attract customers and build your business.</span></p>\n<h2>Celebrate holidaysâ€”even â€œsocial media holidaysâ€</h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Did you know February 18 is National Drink Wine Day? Or how about National Cheese Curd Day on October 15? Regardless of whether these â€œholidaysâ€ are legitimate, one thing is certain: People love any excuse to celebrate.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To take advantage of the occasion, you could offer a complimentary wine tasting next time February 18 rolls around, or a cheese tasting in honor of National Cheese Curd Day in October. Food (or alcohol) is a powerful incentive for getting people through the door.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Social media holidays also offer a timely hook for hosting low-key virtual events that donâ€™t require a lot of money and effort. Instead of an in-store gathering, your boutique pet shop could offer a discount for online orders on National Rescue Dog Day, for example.</span></p>\n<h2>Plan an open house in-person or virtually</h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Sometimes, all it takes to attract new customers is an invitation to come on in.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If youâ€™re opening a new business, if your store has irregular hours, or if you work by appointment only, consider hosting an open house. This gives people a no-pressure way to learn about your business and see your space.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you run a gym, people can stop by and get to know you before committing to their first class. If you own a spa, an open house could inspire visitors to book a massage. All you need for a successful open house is a few snacks, something to sip on, and an invitation. No party planner or red carpet required.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If youâ€™re planning a virtual open house, bring in a special guest or attraction to make your event more enticing. One idea: You could host a Zoom happy hour and bring in a guest bartender to teach attendees how to make a specialty cocktail at home.</span></p>\n<h2>Team up with another small business</h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You run a </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/featured-calendar-ginger-and-baker/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">bakery</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> next to a dog salon. Maybe your neighboring business would let you set up a stand in the salon to sell pet-friendly artisan treats. Then, maybe you can choose a day when all orders from your bakery come with a coupon for grooming.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Chat with your fellow business owners to find opportunities to team up and host low-effort, high-impact events. You never know when your interests might intersect, even if you work in totally different fields.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Joining forces on virtual events is easier than ever with </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/event-management/how-event-planners-can-use-facebook-and-instagrams-new-live-event-features/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">tools like IG Live and Live WIth on Facebook</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, which let you co-host online events with other people.</span></p>\n<h2>Host events related to your business</h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Book stores host authors for book readings. Wine stores host sommeliers for tastings. If you own a pet store, why not bring in an</span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/3-simple-ways-for-dog-trainers-to-make-the-most-of-a-wordpress-calendar/\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">obedience expert</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for a class or webinar on positive reinforcement? If you run a jewelry shop, why not host a jewelry-making class (or </span><a href=\"https://www.tasharae.com/rent-a-jewelry-kit\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">rent out kits with instructions</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> so people can make jewelry at home)? If you own a home dÃ©cor store, how about a workshop, online or in-person, where attendees can tackle a DIY project?</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Host events that draw on your expertise and existing resources. These tend to be budget-friendly and can make your business into a social hub for people in your community. Ultimately, this can be a great way to increase sales and gain customers.</span></p>\n<h2>Use tools of the trade to make event planning easier than ever</h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Youâ€™ve got your great idea, and now youâ€™re ready to turn your existing efforts into an event. Nice! All you need now are a few simple tools to help you manage your events. If you use WordPress to power your business website, check out our full suite of plugins that can power your</span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-events-calendar-pro/\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">events calendar</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">,</span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-event-tickets-plus/\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ticketing</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">,</span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-event-tickets-plus/\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">registration</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">,</span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/promoter/\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">email marketing</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, and more.</span></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-turn-anything-into-an-event-your-audience-will-love/\">How to Turn Anything Into an Event Your Audience Will Love</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:22:\"Event Tickets 4.12.1.1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/event-tickets/event-tickets-4-12-1-1/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s: