hould be smooth sailing when updating. That said, itâ€™s always a good idea toÂ <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-site-backups/\">backup</a>Â your site and test changes in aÂ <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-and-using-a-wordpress-staging-site/\">development environment</a>Â before installing this on your live site, as you would with any other WordPress update.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/event-tickets/event-tickets-4-12-1-1/\">Event Tickets 4.12.1.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"How to Moderate a Virtual Event\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:67:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-moderate-a-virtual-event/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 28 May 2020 21:46:42 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Blog\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"Event Management\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Tips & Tricks\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Virtual Events\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2047642\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:576:\"<p>Virtual events can be great: The convenience! The low overhead! The countless ways to connect with people around the world!Â  But if youâ€™ve ever sat through a painful video call or a boring online class, you know that virtual events can also be a drag if theyâ€™re not executed properly. The key to creating engaging&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-moderate-a-virtual-event/\">How to Moderate a Virtual Event</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Lauren\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9551:\"<p><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/event-management/virtual-events-a-getting-started-guide/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Virtual events</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> can be great: The convenience! The low overhead! The countless ways to connect with people around the world!Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But if youâ€™ve ever sat through a painful video call or a boring online class, you know that virtual events can also be a drag if theyâ€™re not executed properly.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The key to creating engaging online events is moderation. A good host moderates their events to ensure guests are having a great time and staying engaged. That means interacting in the comments, answering questions, and creating a two-way experience rather than just lecturing at attendees.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Before you start your next online event, make sure youâ€™re following these tips for successful moderating.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Moderating: Why does it matter?</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Have you ever been on a webinar where the speaker never looks at the questions in the chat box (or worse, disables chat altogether)? A one-sided event is unengaging. When thereâ€™s no way to participate or interact, attendees may as well be watching a recording.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Some virtual event hosts choose to disable live comments and chats out of fear that the comments will get out of hand. But by designating a moderator and creating a plan for interacting, itâ€™s easy to keep the conversation flowing and on-track.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ultimately, itâ€™s a good business move to moderate your online events: The more you engage with your audience and help keep the conversation moving, the more likely attendees are to show up to your next event.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tools for moderating your event</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Moderating virtual events doesnâ€™t require expensive software or specialized equipment. Hereâ€™s what you need to get started.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>A chat function within your event platform. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Whether youâ€™re </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/event-management/how-event-planners-can-use-facebook-and-instagrams-new-live-event-features/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">livestreaming on social media</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, meeting over Zoom, or broadcasting on webinar software, you probably have a built-in chat feature on your event platform that participants can use to ask questions and talk amongst themselves.</span></b></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>A separate chat or participant forum. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you donâ€™t have a built-in chat feature, or if your event needs a place where participants can also connect before and after your event, create an online gathering spot using Slack or a private Facebook group. This gives attendees a place to convene during your event and a place to stay in touch and ask questions afterwards.</span></li>\n<li>Reminder: Test your tech. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Nothing is worse than showing up on time for a live event and the presenter spends 20 minutes struggling with video or audio settings. Test ahead of time to make sure all your video, audio, screen sharing and other tech is working.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A moderating play-by-play</span></h2>\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Before your event</span></h3>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><b>Give an extra buffer for networking. </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Itâ€™s a good idea to build in about 15 minutes at the beginning of your event for an icebreaker. Give participants a chance to get to know each other and establish rapport before you launch into the main event.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><b>Prep your audience.</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Be direct about your expectations: Should participants have video on or off? Should microphones be muted? This is also a great time to set expectations about how youâ€™ll interact with the audience. Will you be pausing to answer questions, or are you saving questions until the end?</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During your event</span></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Show up prepared. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Virtual events happen online, but theyâ€™re no less â€œrealâ€ than in-person events. You still need to come prepared, which means rehearsing your presentation in advance; if you wing it and fail, your audience will know.</span></b></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>Use your tools. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Some online meeting platforms let moderators mute everyone but the event host, which is an easy way to cut out unwanted background noise during a presentation. You can also use </span><a href=\"https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/206476093-Enabling-breakout-rooms\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">breakout rooms in Zoom</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to split your call into separate sessions.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>Keep the conversation going. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Encourage participants to chime in either in the chat box or on video. Call on people by name to create a more personalized experience.</span></li>\n<li>Read the room.<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> This can be a challenge when youâ€™re connecting over a screen, but itâ€™s not impossible. Watch for facial cues to see if your attendees are engaged, distracted, or bored. You can also ask your audience to weigh in throughout the event using chat.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">After your event</span></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Guide your audience to another space to connect. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Right after your event, share a link to a Slack channel, Facebook group, or another venue where participants can get in touch with you and each other. You may want to create a landing page with links to relevant resources and materials from your event.</span></b></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>Follow up. <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/tips/email-communication-tips-for-online-events/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Send a quick email</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to your audience to gather feedback and to say thanks. </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/event-management/survey-questions-to-ask-attendees-after-an-event/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Post-event communication</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is crucial for fine-tuning your future events with help from audience feedback; itâ€™s also a great time to express your gratitude.Â </span></li>\n<li>Have a strong call to action. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When you follow up with attendees, include a strong call to action to keep them engaged, whether you direct them to a post-event landing page or to a forum where they can stay in touch with each other.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2047648\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1884\" height=\"1305\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist.jpg 1884w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-300x208.jpg 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-665x461.jpg 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-123x85.jpg 123w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-768x532.jpg 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-1536x1064.jpg 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-430x298.jpg 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-645x447.jpg 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-1068x740.jpg 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-460x319.jpg 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-1602x1110.jpg 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-1591x1102.jpg 1591w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-707x490.jpg 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-600x416.jpg 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/moderating-virtual-events-checklist-500x346.jpg 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1884px) 100vw, 1884px\" /></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Looking for more virtual event advice?</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Check out our </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/virtual-event-resources/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">virtual event resources page</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for tips, tricks, and tools to help you make the most of your online events.</span></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-moderate-a-virtual-event/\">How to Moderate a Virtual Event</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:63:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:49:\"Introducing New Shortcodes for Event Tickets Plus\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:90:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/news/introducing-new-shortcodes-for-event-tickets-plus/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 27 May 2020 17:06:37 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Blog\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Tips & Tricks\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"What\'s New\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2044685\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:637:\"<p>Big news for anybody running Event Tickets Plus on their WordPress site: for the first time, Event Tickets Plus officially supports shortcodes! Easily display tickets anywhere on your WordPress site, and an added bonus of the ability to display content based on whether a user has registered for the event or not. We really couldn&#8217;t&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/news/introducing-new-shortcodes-for-event-tickets-plus/\">Introducing New Shortcodes for Event Tickets Plus</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Geoff\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15670:\"<p>Big news for anybody running <strong><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-event-tickets/\">Event Tickets Plus</a></strong> on their WordPress site: <strong>for the first time, Event Tickets Plus officially supports shortcodes! </strong>Easily display tickets anywhere on your WordPress site, and an added bonus of the ability to display content based on whether a user has registered for the event or not.</p>\n<p>We really couldn&#8217;t be more excited for this. It&#8217;s such a big deal that we thought we&#8217;d show &#8217;em off to you and how you can use them to drive ticket sales and create awesome user experiences for your attendees.</p>\n<h3>Awesome, right? Just think of all the ways this ticket shortcode can come in handy:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Adding tickets and RSVPs on more pages to promote the event</li>\n<li>Making targeted landing pages for specific audiences to increase registrations</li>\n<li>Creating a one-stop spot to register for any event</li>\n<li>Cross-promoting events on other event pages</li>\n<li>Adding registration in other spots, like a shopping cart</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Create tickets once, display them anywhere</h2>\n<p>New shortcodes make it super easy to display tickets â€” and yes, RSVPs â€” on any WordPress page or post on your site. Create them as you normally do in the WordPress editor, then drop in either <kbd>[tribe_tickets]</kbd> for tickets or <kbd>[tribe_tickets_rsvp]</kbd> for RSVPs anywhere on your site to display the registration form.</p>\n<p>For example, let&#8217;s say you&#8217;re planning a webinar and are accepting RSVPs for it.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-2044694 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM.png\" alt=\"Screenshot. An event page created with The Events Calendar plugin displaying an RSVP form for the event.\" width=\"2038\" height=\"1660\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM.png 2038w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-300x244.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-665x542.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-104x85.png 104w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-768x626.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-1536x1251.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-430x350.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-645x525.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-2000x1629.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-1068x870.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-460x375.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-1602x1305.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-1353x1102.png 1353w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-651x530.png 651w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-2029x1653.png 2029w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-600x489.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.22.49-AM-500x407.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2038px) 100vw, 2038px\" /></p>\n<p>Normally, the event page would be the only place where someone would be able to register for the event. But now there&#8217;s a shortcode that allows you to drop the registration form on other pages and posts. In this case, all it takes is <kbd>[tribe_tickets_rsvp post_id=\"123\"]</kbd>, where the <kbd>post_id</kbd> is the ID number of the event page. This tells the shortcode to fetch all registrations for that particular event.</p>\n<div id=\"attachment_2044700\" style=\"width: 2322px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2044700\" class=\"wp-image-2044700 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM.png\" alt=\"Screenshot. Showing the WordPress page editor with a shortcode block containing the shortcode to embed the RSVP form for the event on the page.\" width=\"2312\" height=\"2294\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM.png 2312w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-300x298.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-665x660.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-86x85.png 86w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-768x762.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-1536x1524.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-2048x2032.png 2048w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-430x427.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-645x640.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-2000x1984.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-180x180.png 180w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-1068x1060.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-460x456.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-1602x1590.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-1111x1102.png 1111w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-534x530.png 534w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-1666x1653.png 1666w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-150x150.png 150w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-100x100.png 100w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-600x595.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.34.12-AM-500x496.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2312px) 100vw, 2312px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2044700\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">And, yes, it works perfectly with the block editor!</p></div>\n<p>Simply publish the page and â€” <img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f4a5.png\" alt=\"ðŸ’¥\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /><em>boom!</em> â€” we have another registration form for the event!</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2044701\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM.png\" alt=\"Screenshot. The published page showing the RSVP registration form on it.\" width=\"2042\" height=\"1726\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM.png 2042w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-300x254.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-665x562.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-101x85.png 101w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-768x649.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-1536x1298.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-430x363.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-645x545.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-2000x1690.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-1068x903.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-460x389.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-1602x1354.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-1304x1102.png 1304w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-627x530.png 627w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-1956x1653.png 1956w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-600x507.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-9.37.34-AM-500x423.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2042px) 100vw, 2042px\" /></p>\n<h2>Display the people who have registered for an event</h2>\n<p>You know how there&#8217;s an option in Event Tickets to <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/public-attendee-list/\">display the photos of people who have registered</a> for an event? Well, now that can be embedded with a shortcode as well.</p>\n<p><code>[tribe_tickets_attendees post_id=\"123\" title=\"Here\'s who else is going!\"]</code></p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2044752\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed.png\" alt=\"Screenshot. Showing photos of people who have registered for the event in a single row.\" width=\"1683\" height=\"531\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed.png 1683w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-300x95.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-665x210.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-140x44.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-768x242.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-1536x485.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-1680x531.png 1680w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-430x136.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-645x204.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-1068x337.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-460x145.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-1602x505.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-707x223.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-600x189.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/public-attendees-embed-500x158.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1683px) 100vw, 1683px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you have a way to show off all the wonderful folks who are coming to the event! That&#8217;s a great way to encourage others to register as well.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Display content to users if they&#8217;ve registered for the event&#8230; or not</h2>\n<p>This one&#8217;s pretty darn cool. Let&#8217;s say our webinar is like any other webinar and is livestreamed. We want to embed the livestream on our site, but only show it to the people who actually registers for the event.</p>\n<p>Two new shortcodes make that possible, one for tickets and for RSVPs.</p>\n<p>For example, we can drop this into the event page:</p>\n<p><code>[tribe_tickets_rsvp_protected_content]<br />\n&lt;iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/OnSAnAolpmI\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;<br />\n[/tribe_tickets_rsvp_protected_content]</code></p>\n<p>And, hey, now we get a video on the page that only shows up if someone has RSVP&#8217;d for the event.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2044756\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM.png\" alt=\"Screenshot. Showing the embedded video on a page when logged in and registered for the event.\" width=\"2596\" height=\"2080\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM.png 2596w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-300x240.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-665x533.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-106x85.png 106w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-768x615.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-1536x1231.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-2048x1641.png 2048w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-430x345.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-645x517.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-2000x1602.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-1068x856.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-460x369.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-1602x1284.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-1375x1102.png 1375w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-661x530.png 661w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-600x481.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/Screen-Shot-2020-05-15-at-12.43.36-PM-500x401.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2596px) 100vw, 2596px\" /></p>\n<p>This becomes a lot more powerful when using the shortcode&#8217;s parameters. This includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Showing content to users who haveÂ <em>not</em> registered for the event</li>\n<li>Showing content to users who purchased specific types of tickets or RSVPs</li>\n<li>Showing content to user who haveÂ <em>not</em> purchased specific types of tickets or RSVPs</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The things you can do with this are limitless, from showing a call to action for unregistered users to attend the event to displaying special content to those who have already registered, and everything in between. Heck, you can even use it with the other ticket shortcodes to do things like showing the list of other attendees to people who have already registered. There&#8217;s so much you can do here!</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/news/introducing-new-shortcodes-for-event-tickets-plus/\">Introducing New Shortcodes for Event Tickets Plus</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25:\"Events Calendar Pro 5.1.2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:90:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/events-calendar-pro/events-calendar-pro-5-1-2/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 27 May 2020 13:04:39 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"Events Calendar Pro\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2047093\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:609:\"<p>Hey friends! Events Calendar Pro 5.1.2 features a change that allows custom fields from the Additional Fields feature that are added with the Block Editor to be properly saved and displayed as expected. This is a minor release that should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, itâ€™s always a good idea toÂ backupÂ your site and&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/events-calendar-pro/events-calendar-pro-5-1-2/\">Events Calendar Pro 5.1.2</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"Jaime Marchwinski\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1382:\"<p>Hey friends! Events Calendar Pro 5.1.2 features a change that allows custom fields from the Additional Fields feature that are added with the Block Editor to be properly saved and displayed as expected.</p>\n<p>This is a minor release that should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, itâ€™s always a good idea toÂ <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-site-backups/\">backup</a>Â your site and test changes in aÂ <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-and-using-a-wordpress-staging-site/\">development environment</a>Â before installing this on your live site, as you would with any other WordPress update.</p>\n<p>Here are the detailed changes included in this release:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211;Â <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/pro-additional-fields/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Additional Fields</a> are now properly saving and displayed as expected when added with the block editor.</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; <kbd>0 new strings added, 1 updated, 0 fuzzied, and 0 obsoleted</kbd></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/events-calendar-pro/events-calendar-pro-5-1-2/\">Events Calendar Pro 5.1.2</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:60:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25:\"The Events Calendar 5.1.2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/the-events-calendar-5-1-2/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 27 May 2020 13:03:19 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Release Notes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"The Events Calendar\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2047085\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:597:\"<p>Hey friends! The Events Calendar 5.1.2 features some updates to some minor errors that some of our users with WPEngine were experiencing, as well as a fix for an error with theÂ tribe_get_eventsÂ function. This is a minor release that should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, itâ€™s always a good idea toÂ backupÂ your site and test&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/the-events-calendar-5-1-2/\">The Events Calendar 5.1.2</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"Jaime Marchwinski\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1743:\"<p>Hey friends! The Events Calendar 5.1.2 features some updates to some minor errors that some of our users with WPEngine were experiencing, as well as a fix for an error with theÂ <kbd>tribe_get_events</kbd>Â function.</p>\n<p>This is a minor release that should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, itâ€™s always a good idea toÂ <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-site-backups/\">backup</a>Â your site and test changes in aÂ <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-and-using-a-wordpress-staging-site/\">development environment</a>Â before installing this on your live site, as you would with any other WordPress update.</p>\n<p>Here are the detailed changes included in this release:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; We now prevent undefined errors from occurring when using <kbd><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/using-tribe_get_events/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">tribe_get_events</a></kbd>, in part, by forcing a cache refresh.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; This fix prevents <samp>E_ERROR</samp> on the <samp><a href=\"https://docs.theeventscalendar.com/reference/classes/tribe__events__meta__save/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Tribe__Events__Meta__Save</a></samp> construct when dealing with revisions, which some WP Engine customers were seeing.</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; <kbd>0 new strings added, 49 updated, 0 fuzzied, and 0 obsoleted</kbd></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/the-events-calendar-5-1-2/\">The Events Calendar 5.1.2</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"Promoter 1.14.0 and 1.15.0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:71:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/promoter-1-14-0-and-1-15-0/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 25 May 2020 14:35:47 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Release Notes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2046764\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:598:\"<p>Happy Monday!Â You will be happy to know that we released, not one, but two minor releases: Promoter 1.14.0 and 1.15.0. As usual, these changes have been applied automatically to your Promoter account. So you can just sit back and enjoy them. ðŸ˜Ž Here&#8217;s the detailed changelog of what&#8217;s new: Enhancement &#8211; You can now sync&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/promoter-1-14-0-and-1-15-0/\">Promoter 1.14.0 and 1.15.0</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Geoff B.\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2622:\"<p>Happy Monday!Â You will be happy to know that we released, not one, but two minor releases: Promoter 1.14.0 and 1.15.0.</p>\n<p>As usual, these changes have been applied automatically to your Promoter account. So you can just sit back and enjoy them. <img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f60e.png\" alt=\"ðŸ˜Ž\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /></p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s the detailed changelog of what&#8217;s new:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Enhancement</strong> &#8211; You can now sync to Promoter to your calendar if you have a non-root WordPress install. So, for example, if WordPress is installed in a subdirectory of your domain, say, <kbd>example.com/wordpress</kbd>, Promoter will sync you up!</li>\n<li><strong>Enhancement &#8211; </strong>The initial Promoter sync to your calendar is nowÂ <em>twice as fast</em> as before.</li>\n<li><strong>Enhancement &#8211; </strong>We added a daily limit and warnings surrounding the usage of the &#8220;Attendees of All Events&#8221; audience list. These are safeguards against spamming your attendees unintentionally.</li>\n<li><strong>Enhancement &#8211; </strong>If you use our <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/extensions/event-statuses/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">event statuses extension</a>, we have added three new merge tags you can use in messages and shortcuts: Online Event (which pulls in the label), Event Status (which displays the &#8220;Live,&#8221; &#8220;Canceled,&#8221; and &#8220;Postponed&#8221; labels) and Webstream URL (which displays the address of the livestream video).</li>\n<li><strong>Bugfix &#8211;</strong> The initial sync of your calendar with Promoter could get stuck in certain contexts and we have made sure those are fixed up.</li>\n<li><strong>Bugfix &#8211;</strong> Invalid merge tags made the message fail silently. No more!</li>\n<li><strong>Bugfix &#8211;</strong> The next message scheduled to be sent out was not always displayed but now we&#8217;re displaying it as expected.</li>\n<li><strong>Bugfix &#8211;</strong> When using a custom list as an audience to send a message, the actual list name now displays (as opposed to &#8220;0 groups&#8221;).</li>\n<li><strong>Bugfix &#8211;</strong>Â We fixed a few visual glitches, including ones involving message previews, shortcut alignment, tab styling and table styling).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/promoter-1-14-0-and-1-15-0/\">Promoter 1.14.0 and 1.15.0</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:60:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:49:\"How We Make Our WordPress Plugins More Accessible\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:85:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-we-make-our-wordpress-plugins-more-accessible/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 20 May 2020 17:59:32 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Blog\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Learning\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2045794\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:629:\"<p>Accessibility is a top priority for our team at The Events Calendar. In honor of Global Accessibility Awareness Day, we want to share a behind-the-scenes look at some of the ways weâ€™ve made our WordPress calendar plugins more accessible for all users. Weâ€™re always striving to make our products more inclusive, and weâ€™re proud of&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-we-make-our-wordpress-plugins-more-accessible/\">How We Make Our WordPress Plugins More Accessible</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Geoff\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12746:\"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Accessibility is a top priority for our team at The Events Calendar. In honor of </span><a href=\"https://globalaccessibilityawarenessday.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Global Accessibility Awareness Day</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, we want to share a behind-the-scenes look at some of the ways weâ€™ve made our WordPress calendar plugins more accessible for all users.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Weâ€™re always striving to make our products more inclusive, and weâ€™re proud of the strides weâ€™ve made in creating plugins for all people with all abilities. Hereâ€™s a look at some of the ways our plugins put accessibility first.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">1. We choose colors with accessibility in mind.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Weâ€™re careful to design our products with strategically contrasting colors. Color contrast can help people with visual impairments use our products without straining as they read.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The goal in color contrast is to achieve a contrast ratio between foreground and background colors that earns at least </span><a href=\"https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/quickref/#contrast-minimum\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">an AA or AAA grade according to the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (WCAG). The higher the contrast, the higher the grade!Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Luckily, there are tools to help scan and audit contrasts. One of those tools, the </span><a href=\"https://learnui.design/tools/accessible-color-generator.html\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Accessible Color Generator</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, helped us find the right shade of blue for The Events Calendarâ€™s default primary color so that we hit at a WCAG AA rating.</span></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2045802\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2218\" height=\"1972\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade.png 2218w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-300x267.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-665x591.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-96x85.png 96w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-768x683.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-1536x1366.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-2048x1821.png 2048w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-430x382.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-645x573.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-2000x1778.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-1068x950.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-460x409.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-1602x1424.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-1239x1102.png 1239w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-596x530.png 596w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-1859x1653.png 1859w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-600x533.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/WCAG-grade-500x445.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2218px) 100vw, 2218px\" /></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Thatâ€™s a great start, but we also know color isnâ€™t the only factor that impacts contrast. Font sizes are also crucial: Contrast should increase as text gets smaller. As a result, we created our designs with a minimum font size to maintain our rating. Youâ€™ll see what we mean when you look at the buttons in the calendar user interface.</span></p>\n<div id=\"attachment_2045801\" style=\"width: 1908px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2045801\" class=\"size-full wp-image-2045801\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search.png\" alt=\"A view of The Events Calendar search bar\" width=\"1898\" height=\"188\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search.png 1898w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-300x30.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-665x66.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-140x14.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-768x76.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-1536x152.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-430x43.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-645x64.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-1068x106.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-460x46.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-1602x159.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-707x70.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-600x59.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/2-calendar-search-500x50.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1898px) 100vw, 1898px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2045801\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">The calendar search bar features a prominent button thatâ€™s ideal for tap interactions and uses proper color contrasts.</p></div>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But what we chose for our plugin isnâ€™t always what ends up on a userâ€™s site. If you customize your calendar and switch up the colors, make sure youâ€™re maintaining a good WCAG contrast rating. In addition to the Accessible Color Generator, here are two other tools to help you create good contrast:</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://contrast-checker.glitch.me/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">GOV.UK Contrast Checker</span></a></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">WebAIM Contrast Checker</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">2. We use semantic HTML markup to help people that use assistive technology have a great experience with our products.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Did you know that </span><a href=\"https://www.govtech.com/education/Office-of-Civil-Rights-Enforces-Web-Accessibility.html\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">many schools and universities are required by law to make their websites accessible</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">? We do, because lots of colleges and universities use our plugins. Thatâ€™s why we take extra care to write clean code that uses proper semantics and attributes to help screenreaders read the calendar out loud.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That means we wrap things like navigation in a </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&lt;nav&gt;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> element and headers in a &lt;header&gt; element. It might seem small and obvious, but attention to detail is crucial when it comes to ensuring accessibility for all users, including people who rely on screenreaders.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We also use </span><a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Accessibility/ARIA\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ARIA attributes</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to help assistive technology identify and interpret different types of content. Here are a few examples of the attributes youâ€™ll find throughout the plugin:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">aria-label: Provides a label that the screenreader reads on elements that donâ€™t have a discernible label, like a close button that uses â€œXâ€ instead of â€œCloseâ€ as the label.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">aria-readonly: For elements that cannot be edited, like our calendarâ€™s month view container, which a screenreader might recognize as an editable element without the attribute.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">aria-live: Used on elements displayed on a page </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">after</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> the page loads; particularly useful for errors or information the screenreader should be aware of.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">aria-controls: For interactive elements that affect other things on the page, like tabs where clicking controls the content that is displayed on the screen.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">aria-hidden: Tells assistive technology to simply not announce a specific element.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are others, too, and youâ€™ll find those ARIA attributes throughout the plugin.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">3. We properly hide things</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hiding things in CSS is easy, right? Slap </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">display: none;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on an element and it magically goes away!</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But what if a screenreader skips over something important that we hid with CSS?Â </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Screenreaders will pass over anything with </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">display: none;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on it. So instead of relying on that, we use an accessible class to hide an element from a page in a way that assistive technology can still read:</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.a11y-hidden {</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â Â Â Â border: 0;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â Â Â Â clip: rect(0 0 0 0);</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â Â Â Â height: 1px;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â Â Â Â margin: -1px;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â Â Â Â overflow: hidden;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â Â Â Â padding: 0;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â Â Â Â position: absolute;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â Â Â Â width:1px;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">}</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This works by changing the height of an element to a single pixel, then â€œclippingâ€ it out of view. So, the element is still there â€” itâ€™s just hiding without interfering with other things on the page.The A11Y Project has a </span><a href=\"https://a11yproject.com/posts/how-to-hide-content/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">great overview of this technique</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and why itâ€™s considered the gold standard for hiding things without sacrificing accessibility.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">4. We make it easy to navigate with a keyboard</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Navigating a calendar with a keyboard can be tricky. Take the calendarâ€™s month view, for example: You need a way to navigate not just day to day, but inside of a day with multiple events.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We use the tabindex attribute to make sure keyboard users can navigate the calendar in the correct order by pressing the â€œTabâ€ button. There are instances where we might need to tab to an element then be able to tab through the content inside of it. Thatâ€™s where setting tabindex=â€-1â€ comes into play. We use that on widgets, like the datepicker. By setting a negative value, the datepicker can be accessed with the tab key, but the items inside wonâ€™t be included in the tabbing order, unless the datepicker is opened up.</span></p>\n<div id=\"attachment_2045803\" style=\"width: 1090px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2045803\" class=\"wp-image-2045803 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/05/3-nav.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"1080\" height=\"606\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2045803\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">A look at navigating the datepicker using a keyboard.</p></div>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-we-make-our-wordpress-plugins-more-accessible/\">How We Make Our WordPress Plugins More Accessible</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25:\"Event Tickets Plus 4.12.1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:89:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/event-tickets-plus/event-tickets-plus-4-12-1/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 20 May 2020 17:26:11 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18:\"Event Tickets Plus\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2045270\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:658:\"<p>Hey, we&#8217;re stoked to announce support for Event Tickets Plus shortcodes and additional attendee information fields! Even though the features in here are exciting, this is still considered a minor release that should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, itâ€™s always a good idea toÂ backupÂ your site and test changes in aÂ development environmentÂ before installing this&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/event-tickets-plus/event-tickets-plus-4-12-1/\">Event Tickets Plus 4.12.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Courtney\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4974:\"<p>Hey, we&#8217;re stoked to announce support for <a title=\"Event Tickets Plus shortcodes\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/embedding-tickets-and-rsvps/\">Event Tickets Plus shortcodes</a> and additional <a title=\"Attendee Information fields\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/collecting-attendee-information/#Attendee_Information_Options\">attendee information fields</a>!</p>\n<p>Even though the features in here are exciting, this is still considered a minor release that should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, itâ€™s always a good idea toÂ <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-site-backups/\">backup</a>Â your site and test changes in aÂ <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-and-using-a-wordpress-staging-site/\">development environment</a>Â before installing this on your live site, as you would with any other WordPress update.</p>\n<p>Here are the detailed changes included in this release:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Feature</strong> &#8211; We added new field types to choose from when requiring <a title=\"Attendee Information fields\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/collecting-attendee-information/#Attendee_Information_Options\">attendee information</a> on a ticket or RSVP: Email, URL, Date of Birth, Date and Telephone.</li>\n<li><strong>Feature</strong> &#8211; We&#8217;ve added integration with Event Tickets post and event filtering so that the <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/display-a-list-of-attendees-events/#The_Shortcode\"><samp>[tribe-user-event-confirmations]</samp></a> shortcode supports Easy Digital Downloads and WooCommerce.</li>\n<li><strong>Feature</strong> &#8211; <a title=\"Event Tickets Plus shortcodes\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/embedding-tickets-and-rsvps/\">Multiple shortcodes for Event Tickets Plus have been added:</a>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/embedding-tickets-and-rsvps/#Tribe_Tickets_RSVP_shortcode\"><samp>[tribe_tickets_rsvp]</samp></a> and <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/embedding-tickets-and-rsvps/#Tribe_Tickets_shortcode\"><samp>[tribe_tickets]</samp></a> display the purchasing blocks for RSVP and tickets, just RSVP, or just tickets. Both have the <samp>post_id</samp> argument for the post/page/event for which tickets were created.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/embedding-event-attendees/\"><samp>[tribe_tickets_attendees]</samp></a> displays the public list of attendees. It requires the <samp>post_id</samp> of the event to display the attendees and has an optional <samp>title</samp> argument to set the title of the block in the HTML.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/embedding-protected-content/\"><samp>[tribe_tickets_protected_content]</samp> </a>is an enclosing shortcode where any content within its opening and closing tags will only appear if the currently logged in user does (or doesn&#8217;t if <samp>ticketed=0</samp>) have a ticket for the specified <samp>post_id</samp> (defaults to the current post if not set). You may optionally specify the ticket ID(s) in addition to the Post ID, such as <samp>ticket_ids=&#8221;32,50,90&#8243;</samp> which checks if the attendee has a ticket to any matching ticket IDs.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/embedding-protected-content/#RSVP_examples\"><samp>[tribe_tickets_rsvp_protected_content]</samp></a> is an enclosing shortcode where any content within its opening and closing tags will only appear if the currently logged in user either does or doesn&#8217;tÂ have an RSVP for the specified <samp>post_id</samp> (defaults to the current post if not set). You may optionally specify RSVP IDs in addition to the Post ID, such as <samp>rsvp_ids=&#8221;32,50,90&#8243;</samp> which checks if the attendee has an RSVP to any of the RSVP IDs.</li>\n<li>For anyone using our past extension (no longer available) that introduced these shortcodes, the extension will be deactivated automatically to avoid conflicts.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Feature</strong> &#8211; We&#8217;ve updated the <samp>orders-tickets</samp> template to account for a passed post to be of an unregistered post type, such as for an Event post when The Events Calendar plugin is disabled.</li>\n<li><strong>Hooks</strong> &#8211; <a href=\"https://docs.theeventscalendar.com/reference/since/event.tickets.plus4.12.1/\">https://docs.theeventscalendar.com/reference/since/event.tickets.plus4.12.1/</a></li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; <kbd>15 new strings added, 38 updated, 1 fuzzied, and 4 obsoleted</kbd></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/event-tickets-plus/event-tickets-plus-4-12-1/\">Event Tickets Plus 4.12.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:35:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"\n	hourly	\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"updateFrequency\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"\n	1	\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"headers\";O:42:\"Requests_Utility_CaseInsensitiveDictionary\":1:{s:7:\"\0*\0data\";a:6:{s:4:\"date\";s:29:\"Mon, 22 Jun 2020 11:39:48 GMT\";s:12:\"content-type\";s:34:\"application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8\";s:6:\"server\";s:5:\"nginx\";s:13:\"last-modified\";s:29:\"Mon, 22 Jun 2020 03:03:51 GMT\";s:4:\"etag\";s:34:\"\"67fdb7edb32006c4af8896e34cf1da4f\"\